<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-700-346  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 700 346.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 25 1989 v35 n1777 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GAO: AF buying faulty testers. (Government Accounting Office, AirForce)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barrett, Joyce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Air Force is paying $4 million a set for faulty automatic testequipment for its 12 electronic warfare systems according to aGovernment Accounting Office report.andP;  The Air Force failed tocomply with its own acquisition policy that requires testequipment to be deployed at the same time as the warfare system.andO;Manufacturers of the faulty equipment include McDonnell DouglasCorp, Honeywell Inc, General Dynamics Corp, Northrop Corp,Westinghouse Electric Corp, Raytheon Co, and Lockheed Corp. Thedefect in the equipment is its failure to identify systemmalfunctions and faulty components in electronic warfare systems.andO;Error rates as high as 34 percent are commonplace.andP;  One product byMcDonnell Douglas failed to identify 90 percent of themalfunctions during a test of the AKR-56 radar warning receiverand ALQ-135 jammer.andP;  The Air Force relies on outside contractorsto keep the equipment going.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeAutomatic Test EquipmentDefectsDefense ContractsUnited States. Air Force.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>